16_219	0.0	Today, few of the revisionist experts on drug laws dispute crack's link to violence and gangs.
16_220	0.0	``It was a nightmare,'' McCaffrey said.
16_221	0.0	``It was World War III''.
16_222	0.1111111111111111	But crack was never America's drug of choice _ it did not come close.
16_223	0.0	At the height of concern in the late 1980s, the National Household Survey on Drugs estimated that less than one-half of 1 percent of the population over age 12 used crack once a month, while 10 percent used marijuana.
16_224	0.0	And three out of four high school seniors who tried crack did not continue to use it, according to a national survey of students by the University of Michigan.
16_225	0.0	Both surveys have flaws, underestimating inner-city users and high school dropouts.
16_226	0.0	But even after the findings for high use in certain urban areas are adjusted, crack was never the epidemic it was held up to be.
16_227	0.0	The media attention was so hyperbolic that the Drug Enforcement Administration was compelled to correct the record.
16_228	0.0	``Crack is currently the subject of considerable media attention,'' the agency said in 1986.
16_229	0.0	``The result has been a distortion of the public perception of the extent of crack use as compared to the use of other drugs''.
16_230	0.0	Although crack was labeled the world's most addictive drug, 10 years of national surveys have shown that most people who try crack do not continue to use it.
16_231	0.07142857142857142	Because of its intense but short-lived effect, crack does tend to make its users ``psychologically dependent,'' reported a Justice Department study.
16_232	0.0	But numerous studies have shown that crack, like the powder form of cocaine, may be less physically addictive than alcohol or tobacco.
16_233	0.0	The Pyramid Lower-Level Dealers Feel the Sting of Laws Political leaders said harsh sentencing laws were intended to deter use of the most dangerous drugs, with crack at the top of the list.
16_234	0.0	Failing that, they said, the laws would at least go after drug kingpins.
16_235	0.1111111111111111	But statistics show a different pattern among people sentenced to prison for drugs since 1986.
16_236	0.0	Of the people jailed by the federal government for crack offenses, only 5 percent were considered high-level dealers, according to a study by the Sentencing Commission.
16_237	0.0	``The current policy focuses law-enforcement efforts on the lowest level of the distribution line, the street-level dealer,'' the commission's vice chairman, Michael Gelacak, wrote.
16_238	0.0	``Unless we ignore all evidence to the contrary, the current policy has little or no impact upon the drug abuse problem.
16_239	0.0	The jails are full''.
16_240	0.0	nn Supporters of the crack laws say the numbers are explained by the pyramid structure of drug operations; by nature they have few people at the top, lots of people at the bottom.
16_241	0.0	But those at the top are often dealing powder cocaine, with its vastly different penalties.
16_242	0.0	And they are in a position to become informers, the only real hope of beating a mandatory prison term.
16_243	0.0	Had Tonya Drake, the woman serving 10 years for mailing a package, been able to supply what the law labels ``substantial assistance'' _ information on a high-level dealer _ she might have reduced her sentence.
16_244	0.0	The 1980s drug laws leave discretion in the hands of prosecutors to encourage people to ``snitch''.
16_245	0.0	Ms. Drake identified the man who gave her the package, but he was never found.
16_246	0.0	The prosecutor decided her assistance was not substantial.
16_247	0.0	The fixed sentences have infuriated judges, who say they feel their role has been reduced to that of rubber stamps for prosecutors, while their courts are clogged with low- to medium-level drug offenders.
16_248	0.0	``When you're dealing with first-time offenders, you should have some discretion,'' said Lawrence Irving, a former federal judge from San Diego.
16_249	0.0	``I had cases where I was forced to give more jail time for low-level offenders than for the kingpins.
16_250	0.0	It made no sense''.
