16_254	0.0	L.C. Godfrey, one of the ring's wholesale suppliers of cocaine, who was deemed helpful to prosecutors, received nine years.
16_255	0.0	Justice Stephen Breyer of the U.S.
16_256	0.0	Supreme Court said recently that federal judges should regain some of the discretion they once had.
16_257	0.0	Five years ago, Chief Justice William Rehnquist made similar points in condemning the mandatory minimum sentences established by Congress.
16_258	0.0	Dozens of federal judges, most of them former prosecutors, have taken a strong stand against mandatory minimum drug sentences.
16_259	0.0	For these judges, the most significant legacy of crack is a legal system that has left them as little more than spectators in their own courtrooms.
16_260	0.0	The Aftermath The Penalties Outlive Fear of an Epidemic McCaffrey says he came to the drug debate with an open mind but has become convinced that current policies, with the primary emphasis on imprisonment, are failing.
16_261	0.2222222222222222	``The current system is bad drug policy and bad law enforcement,'' he said.
16_262	0.0	On cost alone, arresting, prosecuting and locking up all drug criminals at the price of about $35 billion a year is not effective, he said.
16_263	0.0	He now favors long sentences for dealers and treatment for low-level users.
16_264	0.0	A recent study by Rand Corp.
16_265	0.0	concluded that mandatory jail terms are the least cost-effective way of reducing cocaine consumption.
16_266	0.9333333333333333	For violent crimes, long sentences keep criminals off the street, it reported, but for drug crimes, ``a jailed supplier is often replaced by another supplier''.
16_267	0.0	Drug treatment also has a low success rate; among regular users of cocaine who undergo treatment, only one in eight stops.
16_268	0.0	But even that would achieve a greater reduction in cocaine use _ at a fraction of the cost _ than prison, the Rand study stated.
